# Vendored Zig toolchain (fetched by tools/bootstrap.sh; never committed)
/sdk/zig/

# Kernel-build generated interface headers.
#
# The out-of-tree module builds (drawfs, inputfs, audiofs) run in place
# inside the repo, with SYSDIR pointing at the pinned kernel source, so
# that /usr/src stays a faithful checkout. A side effect is that the
# kernel build's generated interface headers land in the module source
# directory rather than under /usr/obj.
#
# These are derived files: the kernel build produces them from FreeBSD's
# own bus_if.m, device_if.m, pci_if.m and vnode_if.src via
# sys/tools/makeobjops.awk and vnode_if.awk, on every build. Committing
# them would be committing build output that rots against the pinned
# source, and the module source directories in the repo contain only a
# Makefile precisely because the rest is generated.
*/sys/modules/*/bus_if.h
*/sys/modules/*/device_if.h
*/sys/modules/*/pci_if.h
*/sys/modules/*/vnode_if.h
*/sys/modules/*/vnode_if_newproto.h
*/sys/modules/*/vnode_if_typedef.h
*/sys/modules/*/opt_*.h

# Patch files dropped into the repo root while applying them.
/0001-*.patch

# pgsd-loader ELF parser test data.
#
# The *.o rule above is correct for build artifacts. This is not one: it
# is a fixed, known ELF64 relocatable object that module_elf.zig parses in
# its tests, and it must be the SAME bytes everywhere. Regenerating it per
# machine would mean a toolchain difference could silently change what the
# parser is tested against, and the bug it caught (a pointer cast into an
# unaligned buffer) is exactly the kind that depends on byte layout. It is
# 3KB and it is a regression baseline.
!pgsd-loader/src/testdata/*.o

